Orchestrates a single cage run end-to-end for `ctx-cage`: prepare → run → teardown, always tearing down even on failure. The three phases live in private submodules (`prepare`, `run`, `teardown`) purely to satisfy a workspace file-length policy; `run`'s `BwrapConfig` bind/env resolution is further split into a sibling `env` module for the same reason.

`Resolved` is the input struct built by host binaries: target root, task id, mode, absolute paths to the real `ctx-verify`/`ctx-context`/`ctx-scan` binaries, and `allow_dirty` (billed runs on a dirty git tree are refused by default — clean-commit-and-retry is the recovery story).

`execute(r: &Resolved) -> Result<i32, CageError>` is the sole entry point. It first canonicalizes `target_root` via the private `canonicalize_target` — required because `bwrap` binds the target at the identical path inside the cage (ADR-046) alongside always-absolute binds (`/cage/bin`, `/opt/cage/rules.md`, `/run/ctx`); a relative `target_root` would make `bwrap` create mount points as real directories on the host disk instead of inside the sandbox root. Teardown runs unconditionally after `run::run_until_exit`, and its errors are swallowed — only `prepare`/`run` errors propagate.